Victory Boulevard, at the S.E. corner of Austin Place, showing a children's playground on the former site of the Louis De Jonge and Co. paper Manufactory. Across the playground, on Austin Place, is the Roman Catholic Church of Our Lady of Good Counsel.

May 14, 1928

P. L. Sperr

Austin Place, south side, between Victory Boulevard and Ward Ave., showing Our Lady of Good Counsel Roman Catholic Church.

June 12, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.

Austin Place, north side, between Victory Boulevard and Ward Ave. This house was occupied by the Hitchcock family 1853 and 1874 and later by the Stelzner family (1898 to 1917). The dates refer to maps on which the owners' names appear. The view is eastward.

P. L. Sperr.
June 12, 1937.

A closer view of the house, from a different angle.

Austin Place, south side, between Victory Boulevard and Ward Avenue, showing the Roman Catholic Church of Our Lady of Good Counsel. View 1 shows, the front entrance to the church; view 2, the east side of the church; and view 3 the west side, as seen from near Victory Boulevard, across the empty lot, which is the former site of the Louis De Jonge paper factory.
